\
\'93Your feelings are singular. They seem to satisfy every body else.\'94\
\
\'93I suspect they do not satisfy Mrs. Weston. They hardly can satisfy\
a woman of her good sense and quick feelings: standing in a mother\'92s\
place, but without a mother\'92s affection to blind her. It is on her\
account that attention to Randalls is doubly due, and she must doubly\
feel the omission. Had she been a person of consequence herself, he\
would have come I dare say; and it would not have signified whether\
