Highbury. I always say, we are quite blessed in our neighbours.--My dear\
sir, if there is one thing my mother loves better than another, it is\
pork--a roast loin of pork--\'94\
\
\'93As to who, or what Miss Hawkins is, or how long he has been acquainted\
with her,\'94 said Emma, \'93nothing I suppose can be known. One feels that it\
cannot be a very long acquaintance. He has been gone only four weeks.\'94\
\
Nobody had any information to give; and, after a few more wonderings,\
Emma said,\
\
\'93You are silent, Miss Fairfax--but I hope you mean to take an interest\
in this news. You, who have been hearing and seeing so much of late\
on these subjects, who must have been so deep in the business on Miss\
Campbell\'92s account--we shall not excuse your being indifferent about Mr.\
Elton and Miss Hawkins.\'94\
\
\'93When I have seen Mr. Elton,\'94 replied Jane, \'93I dare say I shall be\
interested--but I believe it requires _that_ with me. And as it is some\
months since Miss Campbell married, the impression may be a little worn\
off.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he has been gone just four weeks, as you observe, Miss Woodhouse,\'94\
 said Miss Bates, \'93four weeks yesterday.--A Miss Hawkins!--Well, I had\
always rather fancied it would be some young lady hereabouts; not that\
I ever--Mrs. Cole once whispered to me--but I immediately said, \'91No, Mr.\
Elton is a most worthy young man--but\'92--In short, I do not think I am\
particularly quick at those sort of discoveries. I do not pretend to it.\
What is before me, I see. At the same time, nobody could wonder if\
